{"focus":{"id":"fdf8ecab-ad85-56a9-aaf1-ce95210c4bae","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba040da-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"2.NBT.B.7","description":"Add and subtract within 1000, using concrete models or drawings and strategies based on place value, properties of operations, and/or the relationship between addition and subtraction; relate the strategy to a written method. Understand that in adding or subtracting three-digit numbers, one adds or subtracts hundreds and hundreds, tens and tens, ones and ones; and sometimes it is necessary to compose or decompose tens or hundreds.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["2"],"grade":"2","domain":"NBT","cluster":"2.NBT.B","level":"standard"},"ancestors":[{"id":"f2f75947-1ec6-5a93-b1a4-4931db79b461","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c9da7-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.NBT.A.1","description":"Compose and decompose numbers from 11 to 19 into ten ones and some further ones, e.g., by using objects or drawings, and record each composition or decomposition by a drawing or equation (e.g., 18 = 10 + 8); understand that these numbers are composed of ten ones and one, two, three, four, five, six, seven, eight, or nine ones.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"NBT","cluster":"K.NBT.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"b2e2c061-29b5-5946-be19-19e1a5e8e148","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e93c4-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.OA.A.3","description":"Decompose numbers less than or equal to 10 into pairs in more than one way, e.g., by using objects or drawings, and record each decomposition by a drawing or equation (e.g., 5 = 2 + 3 and 5 = 4 + 1).","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"OA","cluster":"K.OA.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"0465e0ad-eaf2-5d3e-999f-fe665744aaf1","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c9637-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.CC.A.1","description":"Count to 100 by ones and by tens.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"CC","cluster":"K.CC.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"0eb3e5dd-ea32-5ff9-9b5c-9806c54bbbdc","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9dd100-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.OA.A.2","description":"Solve addition and subtraction word problems, and add and subtract within 10, e.g., by using objects or drawings to represent the problem.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"OA","cluster":"K.OA.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"b978b10f-234d-5964-89ed-c132adc07a1f","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9ca104-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.OA.A.1","description":"Represent addition and subtraction with objects, fingers, mental images, drawings, sounds (e.g., claps), acting out situations, verbal explanations, expressions, or equations.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"OA","cluster":"K.OA.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"827a633a-b88a-5ce9-8a7a-18369c547363","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d22e5-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"1.NBT.B.2","description":"Understand that the two digits of a two-digit number represent amounts of tens and ones. Understand the following as special cases:","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["1"],"grade":"1","domain":"NBT","cluster":"1.NBT.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"db51575f-e92e-5a08-904b-66b7b1a5a656","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9bdbaf-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"1.NBT.A.1","description":"Count to 120, starting at any number less than 120. In this range, read and write numerals and represent a number of objects with a written numeral.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["1"],"grade":"1","domain":"NBT","cluster":"1.NBT.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"166aca28-6609-5e57-b6d1-d04b9fad7c63","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9be86e-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"2.NBT.A.1","description":"Understand that the three digits of a three-digit number represent amounts of hundreds, tens, and ones; e.g., 706 equals 7 hundreds, 0 tens, and 6 ones. Understand the following as special cases:","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["2"],"grade":"2","domain":"NBT","cluster":"2.NBT.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"96789744-bebc-5a27-a1d2-6fabaaa79a78","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d2e64-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"2.NBT.A.2","description":"Count within 1000; skip-count by 5s, 10s, and 100s.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["2"],"grade":"2","domain":"NBT","cluster":"2.NBT.A","level":"standard"}],"descendants":[{"id":"3a43a01b-e669-5a5f-b750-631c94388579","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9fdad9-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"2.NBT.B.6","description":"Add up to four two-digit numbers using strategies based on place value and properties of operations.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["2"],"grade":"2","domain":"NBT","cluster":"2.NBT.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"8b539ff6-44c7-59b1-8789-03afc110e85e","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d3a38-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"3.NBT.A.2","description":"Fluently add and subtract within 1000 using strategies and algorithms based on place value, properties of operations, and/or the relationship between addition and subtraction.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["3"],"grade":"3","domain":"NBT","cluster":"3.NBT.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"06f8082b-deb3-5d13-b982-7c012aefc966","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9ecb67-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"4.NBT.B.4","description":"Fluently add and subtract multi-digit whole numbers using the standard algorithm.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["4"],"grade":"4","domain":"NBT","cluster":"4.NBT.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"c15c54d5-0acd-54ef-81bd-f5e0d794df0c","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f62c1-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"4.NBT.B.5","description":"Multiply a whole number of up to four digits by a one-digit whole number, and multiply two two-digit numbers, using strategies based on place value and the properties of operations. Illustrate and explain the calculation by using equations, rectangular arrays, and/or area models.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["4"],"grade":"4","domain":"NBT","cluster":"4.NBT.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"9daac84b-81be-51cd-b208-aaa7d0a0431e","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9fe69c-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"4.NBT.B.6","description":"Find whole-number quotients and remainders with up to four-digit dividends and one-digit divisors, using strategies based on place value, the properties of operations, and/or the relationship between multiplication and division. Illustrate and explain the calculation by using equations, rectangular arrays, and/or area models.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["4"],"grade":"4","domain":"NBT","cluster":"4.NBT.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"9e07be8c-467c-54fe-8589-a689473bbd98","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e2e91-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"4.OA.A.3","description":"Solve multistep word problems posed with whole numbers and having whole-number answers using the four operations, including problems in which remainders must be interpreted. Represent these problems using equations with a letter standing for the unknown quantity. Assess the reasonableness of answers using mental computation and estimation strategies including rounding.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["4"],"grade":"4","domain":"OA","cluster":"4.OA.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"506558bd-685e-5df8-b55d-19dd04a408d8","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f6e17-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"5.NBT.B.5","description":"Fluently multiply multi-digit whole numbers using the standard algorithm.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["5"],"grade":"5","domain":"NBT","cluster":"5.NBT.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"7d15e8c3-103a-5013-a24c-0464999d69a0","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9fed0a-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"5.NBT.B.6","description":"Find whole-number quotients of whole numbers with up to four-digit dividends and two-digit divisors, using strategies based on place value, the properties of operations, and/or the relationship between multiplication and division. Illustrate and explain the calculation by using equations, rectangular arrays, and/or area models.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["5"],"grade":"5","domain":"NBT","cluster":"5.NBT.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"fc0059ec-6efb-5477-913f-2526f51903e2","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba050ca-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"5.NBT.B.7","description":"Add, subtract, multiply, and divide decimals to hundredths, using concrete models or drawings and strategies based on place value, properties of operations, and/or the relationship between addition and subtraction; relate the strategy to a written method and explain the reasoning used.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["5"],"grade":"5","domain":"NBT","cluster":"5.NBT.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"62c2bd03-9006-5597-b8db-1e0a6856dbd3","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c13e2-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"5.MD.A.1","description":"Convert among different-sized standard measurement units within a given measurement system (e.g., convert 5 cm to 0.05 m), and use these conversions in solving multi-step, real world problems.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["5"],"grade":"5","domain":"MD","cluster":"5.MD.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"9140cf9c-bec7-5a10-a1b3-200c0d9d15e4","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e3fc3-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"6.NS.B.3","description":"Fluently add, subtract, multiply, and divide multi-digit decimals using the standard algorithm for each operation.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["6"],"grade":"6","domain":"NS","cluster":"6.NS.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"ad797b48-b738-57dd-a199-03f57fa5160e","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d680b-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"6.NS.B.2","description":"Fluently divide multi-digit numbers using the standard algorithm.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["6"],"grade":"6","domain":"NS","cluster":"6.NS.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"5c31dc9d-3775-5cfe-8ebe-05376dac32dc","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e4aa8-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"7.NS.A.3","description":"Solve real-world and mathematical problems involving the four operations with rational numbers.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["7"],"grade":"7","domain":"NS","cluster":"7.NS.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"e35e05db-06b7-5fe9-a0a1-daea5736f190","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e464c-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"7.EE.B.3","description":"Solve multi-step real-life and mathematical problems posed with positive and negative rational numbers in any form (whole numbers, fractions, and decimals), using tools strategically. Apply properties of operations to calculate with numbers in any form; convert between forms as appropriate; and assess the reasonableness of answers using mental computation and estimation strategies. *For example: If a woman making $25 an hour gets a 10% raise, she will make an additional $\\frac{1}{10}$ of her salary an hour, or $2.50, for a new salary of $27.50. If you want to place a towel bar $9\\frac{3}{4}$ inches long in the center of a door that is $27\\frac{1}{2}$ inches wide, you will need to place the bar about 9 inches from each edge; this estimate can be used as a check on the exact computation.*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["7"],"grade":"7","domain":"EE","cluster":"7.EE.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"374ff999-c31e-5369-9dbe-1887326f03d8","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba1361d-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"7.EE.B.4.a","description":"Solve word problems leading to equations of the form px + q = r and p(x + q) = r, where p, q, and r are specific rational numbers. Solve equations of these forms fluently. Compare an algebraic solution to an arithmetic solution, identifying the sequence of the operations used in each approach. *For example, the perimeter of a rectangle is 54 cm. Its length is 6 cm. What is its width?*","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["7"],"grade":"7","domain":"EE","cluster":"7.EE.B","level":"substandard"},{"id":"67d0c77a-4e09-5cc4-bb0d-033e952ab1ed","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba1b5b2-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"7.EE.B.4.b","description":"Solve word problems leading to inequalities of the form px + q > r or px + q < r, where p, q, and r are specific rational numbers. Graph the solution set of the inequality and interpret it in the context of the problem. *For example: As a salesperson, you are paid $50 per week plus $3 per sale. This week you want your pay to be at least $100. Write an inequality for the number of sales you need to make, and describe the solutions.*","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["7"],"grade":"7","domain":"EE","cluster":"7.EE.B","level":"substandard"},{"id":"3bebaa64-eeef-5329-b3cc-dddc8e68f0a1","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d7eb3-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"8.EE.A.2","description":"Use square root and cube root symbols to represent solutions to equations of the form $x^{2} = p$ and $x^3 = p$, where $p$ is a positive rational number. Evaluate square roots of small perfect squares and cube roots of small perfect cubes. Know that $\\sqrt{2}$ is irrational.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["8"],"grade":"8","domain":"EE","cluster":"8.EE.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"11610aaf-64f0-518d-b9c1-95070a8a7001","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9ef0eb-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"8.EE.A.4","description":"Perform operations with numbers expressed in scientific notation, including problems where both decimal and scientific notation are used. Use scientific notation and choose units of appropriate size for measurements of very large or very small quantities (e.g., use millimeters per year for seafloor spreading). Interpret scientific notation that has been generated by technology.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["8"],"grade":"8","domain":"EE","cluster":"8.EE.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"8d03e081-fa8a-554a-ab0f-ce2b978d9da4","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba1c7ad-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"8.EE.C.7.b","description":"Solve linear equations with rational number coefficients, including equations whose solutions require expanding expressions using the distributive property and collecting like terms.","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["8"],"grade":"8","domain":"EE","cluster":"8.EE.C","level":"substandard"},{"id":"15f1b8b4-b836-5750-866a-f7d5f377a296","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba0b1df-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"8.EE.C.8","description":"Analyze and solve pairs of simultaneous linear equations.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["8"],"grade":"8","domain":"EE","cluster":"8.EE.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"75acceb6-cebe-5b1b-be1c-a9d7dc230f94","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba0e7f4-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"8.G.C.9","description":"Know the formulas for the volumes of cones, cylinders, and spheres and use them to solve real-world and mathematical problems.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["8"],"grade":"8","domain":"G","cluster":"8.G.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"0ab1c3c6-fd11-5ed2-aed7-0b081b5851bf","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c859b-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSN-RN.A.1","description":"Explain how the definition of the meaning of rational exponents follows from extending the properties of integer exponents to those values, allowing for a notation for radicals in terms of rational exponents. *For example, we define $5^{\\frac{1}{3}}$ to be the cube root of $5$ because we want $\\left(5^{\\frac{1}{3}}\\right)^{3} = 5^{\\left(\\frac{1}{3}\\right)3}$ to hold, so $\\left(5^{\\frac{1}{3}}\\right)^{3}$ must equal $5$.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"N-RN","cluster":"HSN-RN.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"09ae5d13-9211-58d4-88a2-f42b6d755699","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c54a3-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-CED.A.1","description":"Create equations and inequalities in one variable and use them to solve problems. Include equations arising from linear and quadratic functions, and simple rational and exponential functions.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-CED","cluster":"HSA-CED.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"8d469405-0fa7-5fc8-86f7-174b02fc1588","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba1507e-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-REI.B.4.a","description":"Use the method of completing the square to transform any quadratic equation in x into an equation of the form $(x - p)^{2} = q$ that has the same solutions. Derive the quadratic formula from this form.","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-REI","cluster":"HSA-REI.B","level":"substandard"},{"id":"3b81e97d-948b-546b-859a-cbcffd5558cd","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba1d10e-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-REI.B.4.b","description":"Solve quadratic equations by inspection (e.g., for $x^{2} = 49$), taking square roots, completing the square, the quadratic formula and factoring, as appropriate to the initial form of the equation. Recognize when the quadratic formula gives complex solutions and write them as a ± bi for real numbers a and b.","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-REI","cluster":"HSA-REI.B","level":"substandard"},{"id":"4ac673fb-a96d-56cd-bc7c-bebb3f39a094","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c8254-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSN-Q.A.1","description":"Use units as a way to understand problems and to guide the solution of multi-step problems; choose and interpret units consistently in formulas; choose and interpret the scale and the origin in graphs and data displays.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"N-Q","cluster":"HSN-Q.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"7bf83ce5-c739-5d93-aef9-fc92540518d5","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d8f41-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-CED.A.2","description":"Create equations in two or more variables to represent relationships between quantities; graph equations on coordinate axes with labels and scales.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-CED","cluster":"HSA-CED.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"ad83f760-4517-5272-a74a-71f8ae9fa783","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e5c5a-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-CED.A.3","description":"Represent constraints by equations or inequalities, and by systems of equations and/or inequalities, and interpret solutions as viable or nonviable options in a modeling context. *For example, represent inequalities describing nutritional and cost constraints on combinations of different foods.*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-CED","cluster":"HSA-CED.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"01b7859e-1dcd-5fa2-a376-427f443f1225","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f8f43-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-REI.C.5","description":"Prove that, given a system of two equations in two variables, replacing one equation by the sum of that equation and a multiple of the other produces a system with the same solutions.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-REI","cluster":"HSA-REI.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"d032100d-1fb4-5b84-be62-4324e9fbfff0","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba00873-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-REI.C.6","description":"Solve systems of linear equations exactly and approximately (e.g., with graphs), focusing on pairs of linear equations in two variables.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-REI","cluster":"HSA-REI.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"3673e4d3-33a5-57f5-91f5-8ed8ec73be0f","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba06a30-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-REI.C.7","description":"Solve a simple system consisting of a linear equation and a quadratic equation in two variables algebraically and graphically. *For example, find the points of intersection between the line $y = -3x$ and the circle $x^{2} + y^{2} = 3$.*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-REI","cluster":"HSA-REI.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"6aecb0a3-a4b9-5122-b7b9-676e192cddf4","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9ca838-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-REI.D.10","description":"Understand that the graph of an equation in two variables is the set of all its solutions plotted in the coordinate plane, often forming a curve (which could be a line).","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-REI","cluster":"HSA-REI.D","level":"standard"},{"id":"8c83a157-7658-5474-88dd-7a221f131105","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9cbd4d-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-REI.D.12","description":"Graph the solutions to a linear inequality in two variables as a half-plane (excluding the boundary in the case of a strict inequality), and graph the solution set to a system of linear inequalities in two variables as the intersection of the corresponding half-planes.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-REI","cluster":"HSA-REI.D","level":"standard"},{"id":"3bf30fb5-71d5-54fb-be47-574fb88880d0","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9fa334-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-GPE.B.5","description":"Prove the slope criteria for parallel and perpendicular lines and use them to solve geometric problems (e.g., find the equation of a line parallel or perpendicular to a given line that passes through a given point).","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-GPE","cluster":"HSG-GPE.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"1e097c63-b820-53c3-85ef-03d9da9e0944","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c70b3-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-GMD.A.1","description":"Give an informal argument for the formulas for the circumference of a circle, area of a circle, volume of a cylinder, pyramid, and cone.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-GMD","cluster":"HSG-GMD.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"3b8fbea4-86ea-5a73-9ebd-e4a2936baf33","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9da784-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-GMD.A.2","description":"(+) Give an informal argument using Cavalieri's principle for the formulas for the volume of a sphere and other solid figures.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-GMD","cluster":"HSG-GMD.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"3f55d232-bf86-54b0-8188-424990f7f7c7","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e70eb-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-GMD.A.3","description":"Use volume formulas for cylinders, pyramids, cones, and spheres to solve problems.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-GMD","cluster":"HSG-GMD.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"ef4ff21d-897e-598d-b731-2d5b8a2b31c3","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c77f2-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-MG.A.1","description":"Use geometric shapes, their measures, and their properties to describe objects (e.g., modeling a tree trunk or a human torso as a cylinder).","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-MG","cluster":"HSG-MG.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"636789d4-4a59-5e0e-91cd-902823701dd5","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e763a-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-MG.A.3","description":"Apply geometric methods to solve design problems (e.g., designing an object or structure to satisfy physical constraints or minimize cost; working with typographic grid systems based on ratios).","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-MG","cluster":"HSG-MG.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"afe011f5-a698-57a4-bc3e-28d8ae8fb9b2","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9db867-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSN-RN.A.2","description":"Rewrite expressions involving radicals and rational exponents using the properties of exponents.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"N-RN","cluster":"HSN-RN.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"b517efad-0cfa-5eb1-994f-70cb48476ba9","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c73d2-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-GPE.A.1","description":"Derive the equation of a circle of given center and radius using the Pythagorean Theorem; complete the square to find the center and radius of a circle given by an equation.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-GPE","cluster":"HSG-GPE.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"d7e1d5de-d82c-5489-a1f3-38fc49b7f9b0","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba0f6fa-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSN-CN.C.9","description":"(+) Know the Fundamental Theorem of Algebra; show that it is true for quadratic polynomials.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"N-CN","cluster":"HSN-CN.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"9354b4ae-34f1-5768-9f99-07b5c9292ee4","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba155d1-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-SSE.B.3.a","description":"Factor a quadratic expression to reveal the zeros of the function it defines.","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-SSE","cluster":"HSA-SSE.B","level":"substandard"},{"id":"ea84de3d-fd6d-5af3-8b08-9116772352db","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9cb182-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-REI.D.11","description":"Explain why the x-coordinates of the points where the graphs of the equations y = f(x) and y = g(x) intersect are the solutions of the equation f(x) = g(x); find the solutions approximately, e.g., using technology to graph the functions, make tables of values, or find successive approximations. Include cases where f(x) and/or g(x) are linear, polynomial, rational, absolute value, exponential, and logarithmic functions.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-REI","cluster":"HSA-REI.D","level":"standard"},{"id":"4c04767d-6e2c-570c-946f-5664dab60615","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9daa46-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-GPE.A.2","description":"Derive the equation of a parabola given a focus and directrix.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-GPE","cluster":"HSG-GPE.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"cb3e6f20-d26c-5f6d-bae5-33d85ede580e","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e7402-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-GPE.A.3","description":"(+) Derive the equations of ellipses and hyperbolas given the foci, using the fact that the sum or difference of distances from the foci is constant.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-GPE","cluster":"HSG-GPE.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"05163bd2-5fa8-58ad-810a-d9d8039062bd","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba237aa-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-SSE.B.3.c","description":"Use the properties of exponents to transform expressions for exponential functions. *For example the expression $1.15^{t}$ can be rewritten as ${(1.15^{\\frac{1}{12}})}^{12t} \\approx 1.012^{12t}$ to reveal the approximate equivalent monthly interest rate if the annual rate is 15%.*","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-SSE","cluster":"HSA-SSE.B","level":"substandard"},{"id":"115f86cd-46ac-576c-9d89-ac5f793ebe03","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d91e7-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-REI.A.2","description":"Solve simple rational and radical equations in one variable, and give examples showing how extraneous solutions may arise.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-REI","cluster":"HSA-REI.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"41648f4d-756c-505d-a856-fa424f3bf56e","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba1e33f-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-IF.C.8.b","description":"Use the properties of exponents to interpret expressions for exponential functions. *For example, identify percent rate of change in functions such as $y = (1.02)^{t}$, $y = (0.97)^{t}$, $y = (1.01)^{12t}$, $y = (1.2)^{\\frac{t}{10}}$, and classify them as representing exponential growth or decay.*","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-IF","cluster":"HSF-IF.C","level":"substandard"},{"id":"8e1de64e-487f-5145-a1ea-cf51f433d2b7","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f16e0-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-GPE.B.4","description":"Use coordinates to prove simple geometric theorems algebraically. *For example, prove or disprove that a figure defined by four given points in the coordinate plane is a rectangle; prove or disprove that the point $(1, \\sqrt{3})$ lies on the circle centered at the origin and containing the point (0, 2).*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-GPE","cluster":"HSG-GPE.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"f7cc5a71-2d54-5197-9757-3b99d3b468a9","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d8c97-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-APR.B.2","description":"Know and apply the Remainder Theorem: For a polynomial p(x) and a number a, the remainder on division by x - a is p(a), so p(a) = 0 if and only if (x - a) is a factor of p(x).","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-APR","cluster":"HSA-APR.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"dd015436-cfc6-59ea-b0de-4053e38a40ff","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f04ba-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-BF.B.4","description":"Find inverse functions.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-BF","cluster":"HSF-BF.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"897aefc4-aadd-5681-b5cb-20ae995b6dfb","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e5a39-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-APR.B.3","description":"Identify zeros of polynomials when suitable factorizations are available, and use the zeros to construct a rough graph of the function defined by the polynomial.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-APR","cluster":"HSA-APR.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"8ff8661c-a3d0-50ba-9876-e9b2432cb761","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f920f-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-BF.B.5","description